    "file": "charts/pawtograder/templates/ingress-channels.yaml",
    "line": 724,
    "summary": "Channel Ingress blindly inherits `$.Values.ingress.annotations` (which on staging/prod contains `cert-manager.io/cluster-issuer: letsencrypt-prod`) while pointing tls[].secretName at the shared reflected `channelWildcardTlsSecret`. This contradicts the documented 'no per-host ACME issuance' design.",
    "failure_scenario": "Operator adds a channel `team7` with default host `team7.staging.pawtograder.net` and relies on the reflected `*.staging` wildcard secret. cert-manager's ingress-shim sees the inherited cluster-issuer annotation + the TLS block and creates a Certificate for `team7.staging.pawtograder.net` that targets `channelWildcardTlsSecret`, fighting the reflector for ownership of that secret and/or firing a per-host Let's Encrypt order (rate-limit risk), exactly the per-host ACME the wildcard approach was meant to avoid. The wildcard secret can get overwritten with a single-SAN cert, breaking TLS for the stable host and every other channel that shares it."
  },
  {
    "file": "Dockerfile",
    "line": 29,
    "summary": "values.yaml instructs channel images to be built with `NEXT_PUBLIC_PAWTOGRADER_WEB_URL=<channel host>`, but this build arg is the same one all auth redirect origins are baked from (app/actions.ts reset-password/signup/OAuth callback). No chart/CI mechanism sets it per-channel, and Helm self-host leaves VERCEL_PROJECT_PRODUCTION_URL empty so the baked value is used unconditionally.",
    "failure_scenario": "A canary `team7` image is built reusing the stable build args (the obvious default, since the arg is required at build), so it bakes `NEXT_PUBLIC_PAWTOGRADER_WEB_URL=https://staging.pawtograder.net`. A student on `team7.staging.pawtograder.net` clicks 'Reset password', confirms a signup email, or logs in via Microsoft OAuth: app/actions.ts builds redirectTo/emailRedirectTo against the STABLE host. Supabase emails a link / sets the OAuth callback to the stable origin; the PKCE code-verifier cookie set on the channel host is not where the callback lands, so the token exchange fails or the user is silently bounced off the canary. Auth flows are broken on every channel host."
  },
