    "line": 56,
    "body": "**cert-manager will fight the reflected wildcard secret.** This Ingress sets `secretName: {{ $tlsSecret }}` to the shared, reflected `channelWildcardTlsSecret` (a `*.<zone>` cert), but the annotations block above inherits `$.Values.ingress.annotations` verbatim — which on staging includes `cert-manager.io/cluster-issuer: letsencrypt-prod` (see `examples/values-staging.yaml:40`).\n\ncert-manager's ingress-shim, seeing a cluster-issuer annotation + a TLS block, will create a `Certificate` for this channel host that targets the same secret, fighting the reflector for ownership and potentially overwriting the shared wildcard with a single-SAN cert — breaking TLS for the **stable host and every other channel** that shares it. (The preview path deliberately omits the issuer annotation for exactly this reason — `examples/values-preview.yaml:41`.)\n\nStrip/override `cert-manager.io/cluster-issuer` on channel Ingresses (the reflected secret is pre-provisioned), or document that it must be unset when `channelWildcardTlsSecret` is used."
  },
  {
    "path": "utils/supabase/middleware.ts",
    "line": 82,
    "body": "**Cross-host redirect and the session-cookie domain are gated on two independent env vars, with nothing coupling them.** This redirect fires whenever `NEXT_PUBLIC_CHANNEL_HOST_SUFFIX` is set, but the auth cookie is only shared across channel hosts when `NEXT_PUBLIC_SESSION_COOKIE_DOMAIN` is set (separate var — line 25 here, plus `client.ts`/`server.ts`).\n\nSet the suffix without the domain (easy to do — the PR lists them as separate operator steps) and every channel hop sends a logged-in user to a host that never receives the host-only auth cookie → `getClaims()` returns nothing → the `/course` guard bounces them to `/sign-in`. Cross-channel sessions silently break, and the half-configured state deploys cleanly.\n\nDerive the cookie domain from the suffix (they encode the same zone), or assert both are set together at startup."
  },
  {
    "path": "utils/channels.ts",
    "line": 34,
    "body": "**`hostForChannel` ignores the chart's documented `channels[].host` override.** It always builds `${channel}.${suffix}`, but the Helm chart lets a channel set an arbitrary `host` (see `values.yaml` channels example and `ingress-channels.yaml`, which serve the channel on that overridden host).\n\nIf an operator uses the override with a non-default value (e.g. `cohort7.staging.pawtograder.net` for channel `team7`), middleware still computes `team7.staging.pawtograder.net` and 302-redirects there — a host with no Ingress/Service → TLS to a host nginx has no rule for → 404/503. The course becomes unreachable for every user not already on that channel.\n\nThe TS layer needs the same channel→host map the chart uses (e.g. inject it as an env-provided table) rather than hardcoding the `<channel>.<suffix>` pattern."
  },
